The presence of a moderate form of conductive hearing impairment.

Hydrocephalus is an active distension of the ventricular system of the brain resulting from inadequate passage of CSF from its point of production within the cerebral ventricles to its point of absorption into the systemic circulation.
An abnormality of the Diencephalon, which together with the cerebrum (telencephalon) makes up the forebrain.
A focal seizure characterized at onset by coordinated motor activity. This often resembles a voluntary movement and may consist of an inappropriate continuation of preictal motor activity.
Any abnormality of the morphology of the major calices or minor calices of the kidney.
Congenital absence or underdevelopment of the colon.
Absence or underdevelopment of the urinary bladder.
Difficulty of a male in achieving orgasm.
A structural anomaly of sperm.
A subtype of colorectal carcinoma with mucin lakes.
Abnormally reduced diameter (cross section) of the clavicles.
The presence of a cyst, fistula, or abscess in the sacrococcygeal region (gluteal crease) characteristically accompanied by hair and skin folds.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of threonine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
A Schmorl's node is the herniation of nucleus pulposus through the cartilaginous and bony end plate into the body of the adjacent vertebra.
Pelvic asymmetry refers to asymmetric positioning of landmarks on the two sides of the pelvis and may have a structural or functional etiology.
Difficulty with discriminating red and green hues.
Greater than average forward and/or lateral protrusion of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones.
Anterior chamber cells with more than 50 cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.
An abnormal increase in the concentration of Tn antigen on glycoproteins.
Increase in size of the left atrium.
An anomolous earwax color. Earwax (cerumen) is usually light to dark brown or orange in color.
Inflammation of the large airways of the lung with rapid onset and short course usually associated with cough, mucus production, shortness of breath, wheezing, and chest tightness.
Low set, steeply sloping shoulders.
A limitation of the range of movement of the shoulder joint.
An abnormally increased level of liver isoforms of alkaline phosphatase, tissue-nonspecific isozyme in the blood.
Aggression towards oneself.

The presence of woolly hair on the scalp. The term woolly hair refers to an abnormal variant of hair that is fine, with tightly coiled curls, and often hypopigmented. Optical microscopy may reveal the presence of tight spirals and a clear diameter reduction as compared with normal hair. Electron microscopy may show flat, oval hair shafts with reduced transversal diameter.
A type of hypoplastic anemia in which the erythrocytes have a normal cell volume (the mean corpuscular volume is within normal limits).
Underdevelopment of the ureter.
Increase in size of the right atrium.
A cataract that occurs congenitally as the result of a developmental defect, in contrast to the majority of cataracts that occur in adulthood as the result of degenerative changes of the lens.
Abnormal response to convulxin as manifested by reduced or lacking aggregation of platelets upon addition of convulxin.
An abnormal narrowing of the orifice of the mitral valve.
A type of primitive reflex characterized by an involuntary contraction of the mentalis muscle of the chin caused by stimulation of the thenar eminence of the palm.
An abnormality of the cortex of the kidney.
Any anomaly in the formation of the bony substance of the sternum.
Ossification affecting the set of cartilages of larynx.
An increased lymphocyte count in the cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormal resistance to glucose, i.e., a reduction in the ability to maintain glucose levels in the blood stream within normal limits following oral administration of glucose.
Abnormally increased thickness of the nasal septum.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of phytanic acid in the blood circulation.
Reduced desire for sexual activity on the part of a male.

Streaming or smearing of the Z band, which is then no longer confined to a narrow zone which bisects the I band. The Z disc may extend across the I band or the entire sarcomere in a zigzag manner. Focal thickening, smudging, and blurring of the Z band takes place concurrently. Myofibrillar disorganization is a frequent but not invariable accompanying change.
The presence of a size difference between the left and right cornea.

A type of bladder dysfunction caused by neurologic damage. Neurogenic bladder can be flaccid or spastic. Common manifestatios of neurogenic bladder are overflow incontinence, frequency, urgency, urge incontinence, and retention.
Displacement of the heart outside the thoracic cavity and into the abdomen.
Coarse facial features reminiscent of those of a boxer.
A sensation of stiffness in the joints that occurs following waking up in the morning.

An overriding aorta is a congenital heart defect where the aorta is positioned directly over a ventricular septal defect, instead of over the left ventricle. The result is that the aorta receives some blood from the right ventricle, which reduces the amount of oxygen in the blood. It is one of the four conditions of the Tetralogy of Fallot. The aortic root can be displaced toward the front (anteriorly) or directly above the septal defect, but it is always abnormally located to the right of the root of the pulmonary artery. The degree of override is quite variable, with 5-95% of the valve being connected to the right ventricle.
Reduced functioning of the vestibular apparatus.
A neurological anomaly with gross overeating associated with an abnormally strong desire or need to eat.
Significantly decreased level or failed detection of surfactant protein B in broncho-alveolar lavage fluid.
Abnormal concentration of urate in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

A skin lesions that resembles the lesions observed in psoriasis, viz., an erythematous plaque covered by fine silvery scales. Psoriasiform lesions can be observed in psoriasis as well as in other conditions including allergic contact dermatitis, seborrhoeic dermatitis, Atopic dermatitis, pityriasis rubra, and lichen simplex chronicus.
An anomaly of the the pubic bone, i.e., of the ventral and anterior of the three principal components (publis, ilium, ischium) of the hip bone.
An inflammatory cellular deposit deposited on the corneal endothelium and visible as spots on the cornea.

Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of an icosanoid (also known as eicosanoids). These are signaling molecules derived from oxidation of 20-carbon fatty acids. Most are produced from arachidonic acid, a 20-carbon polyunsaturated fatty acid (5,8,11,14-eicosatetraenoic acid).
A sensation of tightness in the ankle joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.
A congenital defect of heart development characterized by origin of both pulmonary artery and aorta from the morphological left ventricle.
Urge incontinence is the strong, sudden need to urinate.
Head movements associated with nystagmus, that may represent an attempt to compensate for the involuntary eye movements and to improve vision.
Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses.
Delayed or lack of conduction of atrial depolarizations through the atrioventricular node to the ventricles.
A functional anomaly of the gallbladder.
A type of ventricular tachycardia characterized by polymorphioc QRS complexes that change in amplitue and cycle length, and thus have the appearance of oscillating around the baseline in the EKG.
Fixed sarcastic grimace and anxious expression. Caused by spasms of the masseter and other facial muscles.
An abnormal concentration of high-mannose N-glycans on glycoproteins.
A developmental disturbance with extreme ureteral dilatation.

A type of antinuclear antibody (ANA) positivity revealed by indirect immunofluorescence (IFL). The multiple nuclear dots (MND) pattern is immunomorphologically characterized by the staining of 3-20 dots of variable size distributed all over the cell nucleus, but sparing the nucleoli, and, in contrast to the anticentromere pattern, MND reactivity does not stain the chromosomes in mitotic cells.
Any structural abnormality of the medulla of the kidney.
A decrease in the level of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase in the blood.
A lack of facial expression often with staring eyes and a slightly open mouth.
Episodes of muscle weakness associated with elevated levels of potassium in the blood.
Abnormal increase in size of the coronary sinus.

Nephrotic syndrome is a collection of findings resulting from glomerular dysfunction with an increase in glomerular capillary wall permeability associated with pronounced proteinuria. Nephrotic syndrome refers to the constellation of clinical findings that result from severe renal loss of protein, with Proteinuria and hypoalbuminemia, edema, and hyperlipidemia.
A developmental anomaly characterised by focal obliteration of the proximal segment of a bronchus. The bronchial pattern is entirely normal distal to the site of stenosis.
Focal proliferation of glial cells in the hypothalamus.
An ulcer, that is, an erosion of an area of the gastric mucous membrane.
An abnormal white reflection from the pupil rather than the usual black reflection.

The cardinal symptom is severely pruritic skin lesions. Macular, papular, papulovesicular, urticarial, multiforme- and plaque-like variants are differentiated morphologically, hence the name polymorphous. Usually one morphology dominates in a single individual (monomorphous). The skin lesions develop a few hours to several days after sun exposure. Initially, patchy erythema develops, accompanied by pruritus. Distinct lesions then develop. The upper chest, upper arms, backs of the hands, thighs, and the sides of the face are the primary localizations. The skin lesions resolve spontaneously within several days of ceasing sun exposure and do not leave behind any traces.
Dilatation of the vestibule of the inner ear.
An abnormality of the jejunum, i.e., of the middle section of the small intestine.
Any structural anomaly of the portion of the aorta that arises from the base of the left ventricle and extends upward to the aortic arch and from which the coronary arteries arise.
A nodule of the skin that exhibits an increased amount of pigmentation.
Abnormal secretion of the platelet dense-granule content adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
Incidents in which a piece of food or other objects get stuck in the upper airway and provoke coughing, gagging, inability to talk, and difficulty breathing.
Inflammation of the retina of the eye.
An abnormality of renal absorption.
A deformity of foot and ankle in which the foot is bent down and outwards.
Abnormal loss of protein from the digestive tract related to excessive leakage of plasma proteins into the lumen of the gastrointestinal tract.

Partial or complete wasting (loss) of muscularois propria tissue that was once present. The atrophy may involve a marked vacuolar degeneration of myocytes, loss of muscle fibers and some cases a highly characteristic honeycomb fibrosis.
Splitting of the neuroretinal layers of the retina.
The presence of abnormal calcium deposition of the intervertebral disk.

A type of ataxia characterized by the inability to carry out movements with the correct range and motion across the plane of more than one joint related to incorrect estimation of the distances required for targeted movements.
An abnormal in the concentration of core 1 O-glycans on glycoproteins.
Lack of skin pigmentation (coloring).
Repeated transient episodes of metabolic acidosis, that is, of the buildup of acid or depletion of base due to accumulation of metabolic acids.
Reduced ability to transform factor X into its activated form factor Xa.
Reduced or lacking hair growth in the temporal region (i.e., around the temples on the side of the skull).
A moderate delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
A malposition of the pupil owing to a developmental defect of the iris.
A deviation from the normal concentration in the circulation of sex hormone-binding globulin, a circulating glycoprotein that transports testosterone and other steroids in the blood.
A single arterial trunk arises from the cardiac mass. The pulmonary arteries, aorta and coronary arteries arise from this single trunk with no evidence of another outflow tract.
A deviation from the normal circular shape of the pupil
Increased width (cross-sectional diameter) of the clavicles.

Any structural anomaly of the interstitium of the kidney. The renal interstitium is defined as the intertubular, extraglomerular, extravascular space of the kidney. It is bounded on all sides by tubular and vascular basement membranes and is filled with cells, extracellular matrix, and interstitial fluid.
Any structural anomaly of the muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the right ventricle of the heart (cardiac trabeculae, trabeculae carneae).
A congenital anomaly of the urinary tract, in which the kidney is duplicated and is drained via two separate renal pelves and ureters.
A sensation of tightness in the wrist joint when attempting to move it, especially after a period of inactivity.
Increased concentration of glial fibrillary acidic protein in cerebrospinal fluid.
Increased bulk of tissue alongside the nose. The fullness can be caused by both bony and soft tissues.
An abnormality of the outflow tract of the left ventricle.
Underdevelopment of the vertebral artery.
An abnormal growth that projects from the mucous membrane of the urinary bladder.
Abnormally increased levels of leucine in cerebrospinal fluid.

Reduced amplitude (height) of the QRS complex of the electrocardiogram (EKG), defined as amplitudes of all the QRS complexes in the limb leads are less than 5 mm or amplitudes of all the QRS complexes in the precordial leads less than 10 mm.

Preauricular sinus is an occasional finding and most frequently appears as a small pit close to the anterior margin of the ascending portion of the helix. The opening has also been reported along the postero superior margin of the helix, the tragus or the lobule. Preauricular sinus may lead to the formation of a subcutaneous cyst that is intimately related to the tragal cartilage and the anterior crus of the helix.
A type of resting tremor characterized by simultaneous rubbing movements of thumb and index fingers against each other.

Nodules of heterotopia along the ventricular walls. There can be a single nodule or a large number of nodules, they can exist on either or both sides of the brain at any point along the higher ventricle margins, they can be small or large, single or multiple.
The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the cerebrum, also known as the telencephalon, the largest and most highly developed part of the human brain.
A bilateral form of developmental dysplasia of the kidney.
A type of gastritis characterized by excessive proliferation of the gastric mucosa and diffuse thickening of the gastric mucosal folds.
An abnormally decreased sodium concentration in the blood.
Upward and/or sideward growth of anterior hair.
One or more of the leaflets (cusps) of the tricuspid valve bulges back into the right atrium upon contraction of the right ventricle.
Any structural anomaly of the annulus of the mitral valve. The annulus is a ring composed of fibrous and myocardial tissue and is the structure onto which the cusps of the valve attach.
Hypersensitivity in form of an adverse immune reaction against nut food products.
Increased width of the inferred cross-section of the inferior crus.
Naevus flammeus localised in the skin of the neck. This is one of the most common birthmarks and present in approximately 25% of all newborns.
Complete absence of all nasal structures.
A congenital malformation of the tricuspid valve characterized by leaflet deformation.
Generalized non-convulsive status epilepticus without coma is a type of status epilepticus without prominent motor signs, which is electrographically generalized. It is a prolonged absence seizure.
An increased concentration of L-phenylalanine in the blood.
Peripheral visual field constriction with 20-49 degrees binocular visual field preserved.

The two portions of the clavicle (corresponding to the two primary ossification centers of the clavicle) are connected by a fibrous bridge that is contiguous with the periosteum, and a synovial membrane develops, resulting in a clavicle with a bipartite appearance radiographically. Congenital pseudarthrosis of the clavicle generally presents as a painless mass or swelling over the clavicle.
Absence of the acoustic reflex, an involuntary contraction of the stapedius muscle that occurs in response to high-intensity sound stimuli.

Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) whereby one of the two pulmonary artery branched does not arise from the common pulmonary trunk, but instead from the ductus arteriosus or directly from the aorta.
Increased addition of sialic acids to N-linked glycans.
An abnormal reduction in the volume of fluid filtered out of plasma through glomerular capillary walls into Bowman's capsules per unit of time.
A type of nephrogenic rest usually representing single lesions within the renal lobe, renal sinus, or calyceal walls.
Obstruction affecting the biliary tree.
Presence of abnormal convexity of the upper and lower end plates of the vertebrae, i.e., an exaggerated bulging out of the upper and lower vertebral end plates.
An inflammation of the choroid and retina.
Enuresis occurring during waking hours of the day.
An abnormally reduced concentration of glycine in the blood.

Interstital aggregates of histiciocytes, occasionally multinucleated with associated lymphoplasmacytic and occcasionally eosinophilic inflammation. Organization can range from poorly-to-well defined and multinucleated giant cells may be present.
Increased density of the compact bone of long bone.
An abnormally decreased magnesium concentration in the blood.
Increased amount of keratin (visible as white scales) surrounding hair follicles.
An abnormality of the lingual frenulum, that is of the small fold of mucous membrane that attaches the tongue to the floor of the mouth, or the presence of accessory frenula in the oral cavity.
Absence of the normal opening of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture) as a result of an obstructing choanal membrane that may be thin and strandlike or thick and pluglike.
Exaggerated concavity of the anterior or posterior surface of the vertebral body, i.e., the upper and lower vertebral endplates are hollowed inward.
Columella extending inferior to the level of the nasal base, when viewed from the side.
A type of megaloblastic anemia that improves upon administration of pyrimidine supplements such as uridylic acid and cytidylic acid.
The presence of dilatation of the renal pelvis.
Increased susceptibility to infections with Burkholderia cepacia, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection with this agent.
An abnormality of the lip.
A developmental defect in which a kidney is located in an abnormal anatomic position.
Abnormally increased levels of phenylalanine in cerebrospinal fluid.
A reduction in the thickness of Descemet's membrane.

Corneal guttata are droplet-like accumulations of non-banded collagen on the posterior surface of Descemet's membrane. The presence of focal thickenings of Descemet's membrane histologically named guttae. Cornea guttata can be easily diagnosed in vivo and ex vivo by means of specular microscopy as it gives dark areas where no endothelial cells are visible.

The condition in which both atria are joined to the left ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. Usually there is a hypoplastic right ventricle, which may be on the opposite side of the heart as usual.
An erosion of the mucous membrane in a portion of the ileum.
Abnormal thickening of the skin of the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet.

Maturation arrest (MA) is defined as germ cells that fail to complete maturation. Uniform MA is characterized by spermatogenic arrest at the same stage of spermatogenesis throughout the seminiferous tubules. MA is subcategorized into early MA, in which only spermatogonia or spermatocytes are found, and late MA, in which spermatids are detected without spermatozoa.

The doll's eye reflex (also known as oculocephalic reflex) is a test of brain function that is performed in comatose patients by elevating the head roughly 30 degrees and rapidly rotating the head from side to side with the eyes kept open. A normal response is for the eyes to move in the opposite direction. If the eyes do not move in the opposite direction this may indicate severe brain damage.
A lack of mobility of ejaculated sperm.
Occurrence of generalized epileptiform discharges during photic stimulation.
An decreased concentration of tyrosine in the blood.
An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the abdominal aorta.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the internal carotid artery wall.
A complete loss of the ability to perceive vibration.
An anomaly of the sacroiliac joint, which connects the base of the spine (sacrum) to the ilium (a hip bone).
An increased density (number and tightness) of the muscular columns which project from the inner surface of the left ventricles of the heart (cardiac trabeculae, trabeculae carneae).
Deterioration of the tissues of the lateral corticospinal tracts.
Subcutaneous nodules that are located in the vicinity of joints.
An isolated cyst of the kidney.
A congenital malformation with abnormal connection between one of the coronary arteries and a heart chamber or another blood vessel.

Thickening of the interlobular septa of the lungs as seen on a high-resolution computed tomography scan with an irregular appearance of the interlobular septa. THis feature is often associated with distortion of lung architecture.
A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration in the legs.
Apparently small scrotum for age.

Abnormal transferrin isoform profile consistent with a type I congenital disorder of glycosylation. In the traditional nomenclature for congenital disorders of glycosylation, absence of entire glycans was designated type I, and loss of one or more monosaccharides as type II.
Significant luminal narrowing of a long segment of the descending aorta.
A form of manifest strabismus (heterotropia) in which one eye is deviated downwards when both eyes are open.
A nodular pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography that displays a tree-in-bud pattern, representing centrilobular branching structures that resemble a budding tree.
Hypoplasia of the kidney.
An abnormally decreased calcium concentration in the blood.
Descreased amplitude of eletrical response upon electroretinography.
Abnormal smallness of the lens.

A congenital defect of the macula distinct from coloboma associated with optic fissure closure defects. Macular coloboma is characterized by a sharply defined, rather large defect in the central area of the fundus that is oval or round, and coarsely pigmented.
Horizontal nystagmus dating from or present at birth.
Linear heterotopia spanning from the cerebral mantle from the pia to the ependyma.
A morphological abnormality of epiphyses whereby they are abnormally outwardly curving (protuberant).
An abnormal dilation of the rectum. There is a large filled rectum as a result of underlying innervation or muscular abnormalities, which remains after disimpaction of the rectum.
Decreased concentration of methylcobalamin. Methylcobalamin is a form of vitamin B12.
Deposits accumulating between the outer retina and the retinal pigment epithelium and that have a focal distribution.
Lack of skin pigmentation (coloring) of the chest.
Fetal megacystis is an abnormally enlarged bladder identified at any gestational age.
Decreased addition of fucose sugar units to N-linked glycans.
An anomaly of the process of rib bone formation.
Abnormally decreased levels of tyrosine in cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormal enlargement of the renal calices, the system of ducts of the kidney that collect urine.
A mild delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.
An abnormally increased magnesium concentration in the blood.

Elevation of the voltage (height) of the QRS complex. There are several criteria in use, but the most common is the Sokolov-Lyon criterion (S wave depth in V1 + tallest R wave height in V5-V6 greater than 35 mm).
Focal seizure with eyelid myoclonia, not eyelid myoclonias in the context of absence seizures.
Episodes of intense fear, screaming and flailing although affected individuals are still asleep.
Enuresis occurring during sleeping hours.

An abdominal wall defected related to a developmental anomaly of the allantois, which is an embryonic structure that develops as a diverticulum off the yolk sac at about 16 days post fertilization. During further development, the allantois becomes incorporated into the body of the embryo, connecting the ventral aspect of the urogenital sinus (which will develop into the upper pole of the urinary bladder) to the external portion of the umbilicus. Upon further development, the lumen of the allantois becomes obliterated and forms a thick fibrous cord called the urachus, which connects the apex of the bladder to the umbilicus. In adults, the urachus is known as the median umbilical ligament. Failure of the allantoic cavity to obliterate can result of one of four conditions: 1) congenital patent urachus (a completely open connection between bladder and umbilicus); 2) vesicourachal diverticulum (a diverticulum off the bladder but not communicating with the umbilicus); umbilical cyst and sinus (not communicating with the bladder); and 4) alternating urachal sinus. An abdominal wall defect can be associated with a urachal cyst.
Atrophy of the tibialis muscle.
A focal autonomic seizure characterised by impaired awareness at some point within the seizure.
A lack of platelet alpha granules. This typically results in the grey appearance of platelets in giemsa stained blood smears.
Areas of the retina lacking pigmentation. Punched out areas of chorioretinal hypopigmentation less than 1 disc diameter in size and tending to be located in the midperiphery of the retina.
Progressive destruction of the small-to-medium bile ducts of the intrahepatic biliary tree, which leads to progressive cholestasis and often end-stage liver disease.

Fluid which has escaped from retinal blood vessels with a high concentration of lipid, protein, and cellular debris with a typically bright, reflective, white or cream colored appearance on the surface of the retina.

Abnormality of the iris characterized by, typically bilateral, complete or partial iris hypoplasia. The phenotype ranges from mild defects of anterior iris stroma only to almost complete absence of the iris.
Increased numbers of neutrophils in the interstitial tissues of the kidney.
Punctate opacification (reduced transparency) of the corneal stroma.
Limbus-to-limbus corneal thinning, often greatest in the periphery, with globular protrusion of the cornea.
Peripheral visual field constriction with <10 degrees central field preserved.

A type of megaloblastic anemia that does not improve upon administration of folate. Since vitamin B12 acts by promoting recycling of folate, administration of vitamin B12 also does not improve this type of anemia.
A particular type of dementia characterized by a pattern of mental defects consisting prominently of forgetfulness, slowness of thought processes, and personality or mood change.
An elevation beyond the normal concentration of palmitate (palmitic acid) in the blood circulation.
An abnormality of the Common bile duct, a tube-like anatomic structure in the human gastrointestinal tract, formed by the union of the Common hepatic duct and the Cystic duct from the gall bladder.
Increased concentration of urate in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Dilatation of the bladder postnatally.

The accumulation of collagen and related extracellular matrix (ECM) molecules in the interstitium of the kidney. The interstitium is expanded by the presence of collagen that stain blue on trichrome. Tubules are not back to back, but rather separated by fibrosis and can be atrophic.
Recurrent episodes of decreased concentration of glucose in the blood occurring during the infantile period.
An abnormality related to a defect of vertebral separation of cervical vertebrae during development.
An abnormal reduction in the mobility of ejaculated sperm.
Any structural anomaly of the hippocampus,

A wavering, unsteady voice that reflects involuntary and approximately sinusoidal oscillation of motor unit firings of laryngeal muscles. Vocal tremor results in low frequency modulations of voice frequency or amplitude and intermittent voice instability.

The condition in which both atria are joined to a single ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. The morphology of this ventricle does not allow one to determine if it corresponds to the left or right ventricle.
Papilledema refers to edema (swelling) of the optic disc secondary to any factor which increases cerebral spinal fluid pressure.
The right common carotid artery normally originates from the brachiocephalic artery. This term refers to an origin of this artery directly from the aorta.
Absence of nail of little finger.

A nocturnal episode characterized by disorientation, grogginess, and, at times, substantial agitation upon awakening from slow-wave sleep or following forced awakenings. These characteristics might present as agitation, crying or moaning, disorientation, and particularly slow mentation on arousal from sleep (i.e., sleep inertia). The duration of episodes is typically 5 to 15 min but they might last up to several hours.
Recurrent infections by bacteria of the genus Neisseria, including N. meningitidis (one of the most common causes of bacterial meningitis).
Focal (localized) slow activity reflects focal dysfunction, not diffuse dysfunction (i.e., encephalopathy).

Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at one or more long bones in the radius, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.
A decreased amount of valine in the blood.

The presence of foam cells, a type of macrophage that localizes to fatty deposits on blood vessel walls, where they ingest low-density lipoproteins and become laden with lipids, giving them a foamy appearance.
Underdevelopment of the vertebral artery on both sides.
An increased concentration of threonine in the blood.
Abnormally increased levels of isoleucine in cerebrospinal fluid.
An abnormally decreased concentration of transferrin in the blood circulation.

A developmental defect characterized by the lack of aortic valve cusps (leaflets). There may be remnants of the aortic valve in form of a nonobstructive fibrous ridge or rudimentary leaflets or sinuses of Valsalva.
Neonatal electro-clinical motor seizure is a type of neonatal electro-clinical seizure with predominant motor features.
An ichthyosiform abnormality of the skin with congenital onset.
The QRS complexes of the electrocardiogram alternate in height.

A seizure characterized by elementary visual hallucinations such as flashing or flickering lights/colours, or other shapes, simple patterns, scotomata, or amaurosis as its first clinical manifestation.
A type of cataract with punctate opacities of the lens.
A type of focal myoclonic seizure during which awareness is fully retained throughout.
A focal motor seizure with dysarthria / anarthria characterized by impaired awareness at some point during the seizure.
The presence of a notch in the margin of the ala nasi.

Hepatic failure refers to the inability of the liver to perform its normal synthetic and metabolic functions, which can result in coagulopathy and alteration in the mental status of a previously healthy individual. Hepatic failure is defined as fulminant if there is onset of encephalopathy within 4 weeks of the onset of symptoms in a patient with a previously healthy liver.
An episodic form of supraventricular tachycardia with abrupt onset and termination.
An increased concentration of methionine in the blood.

Retinitis pigmentosa inversa is form of retinal degeneration characterized by areas of retinal/chorioretinal degeneration with pigment migration in the macular area (in contrast to retinitis pigmentosa which, at early disease stages, predominantly affects the retinal periphery).
The left main coronary artery (LMCA) is absent and the left anterior descending (LAD) and left circumflex (LCX) arteries arise from separate but adjacent ostia in the left sinus of Valsava.
An abnormal increase in the concentration of disialylated core 1 O-glycans on glycoproteins.
Chronic cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) lymphocytosis is defined as the finding, in at least two serial CSF examinations, of more than 5 cells per cubic millimeter.
Abnormally increased levels of methionine in cerebrospinal fluid.
A type of nephrogenic rest associated with multiple lesions in the periphery of the renal lobe.
Horizontal nystagmus made apparent by looking to the right or to the left.
A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance between the vertebral endplates.
Hypoplasia of the pancreas.
The deposition of calcium salts in the parenchyma of the renal medulla (innermost part of the kidney).

A circumscribed, solid elevation of skin with no visible fluid, varying in size from a pinhead to less than 10mm in diameter at the widest point that is composed of localized hyperkeratosis (the latter may be demonstrated histopathologically).
Histopathological findings of inflammation of the renal interstitium potentially involving fibrotic as well as non-fibrotic areas, composed of lymphocytes, monocytes, plasma cells.
Abnormally increased levels of tryptophan in cerebrospinal fluid.
A failure to achieve the ability to sit at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children sit with support at 6 months of age and sit steadily without support at 9 months of age.
Increase in bulk of the ala nasi.
An abnormal elevation of phytanic acid.
Abnormally increased variability of the size of the vertebral bodies.
Increased protrusion of the inferior crus relative to the prominence of the antihelix stem.
Ultra-low vision but with retained ability to perceive the difference between light and dark.

Osteomalacia is a general term for bone weakness owing to a defect in mineralization of the protein framework known as osteoid. This defective mineralization is mainly caused by lack in vitamin D. Osteomalacia in children is known as rickets.
An increased concentration of proline in the blood.
Testis in inguinal canal. That is, absence of one or both testes from the scrotum owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the scrotum.
A reduced level of the complement component C7 in the blood circulation.
The presence of multiple cysts at the border between the renal cortex and medulla.
A nonprogressive (i.e., stationary) form of difficulties with night blindness with congenital onset.

Refractive error in which the vertical meridian is relatively hypermetropic and the horizontal meridian is relatively myopic (or ocular astigmatism in which the refractive power of the horizontal meridian is the greatest).
The pulsation of the posterior tibial artery behind the internal malleolus, or of the dorsalis pedis artery, cannot be detected on physical examination.
An increased amount of serine in the blood.
More than one fracture of the ribs.
An increased concentration of leucine in the blood.

Absence of the outer dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, which normally are situated outside of the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.
An abnormal decrease in the concentration of core 1 O-glycans on glycoproteins.
A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary head nodding at onset.
A bifid rib refers to cleavage of the sternal end of a rib, usually unilateral. Bifid ribs are usually asymptomatic, and are often discovered incidentally by chest x-ray.
Coarctation of the aorta is a narrowing or constriction of a segment of the abdominal aorta.
An elevation in the concentration of interferon gamma measured in the blood circulation.
Abnormally increased formation of dense trabecular bone tissue. Despite the increased density of bone tissue, osteopetrotic bones tend to be more fracture-prone than normal.
A type of transposition of the great arteries (TGA) in which aorta is in front of and primarily to the right of the pulmonary artery. This is the most common kind of TGA.
Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with an asymmetrical pattern of hypertrophy, with a predilection for the interventricular septum and myocyte disarray.
A defect in the ability to concentrate the urine.
Thinned, deficient, or excessively arched ala nasi.
An abnormal localized reduction in amplitude of the cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
Increased addition of mannose to N-linked glycans.
An increased concentration of tyrosine in the blood.
A structural abnormality of the sperm head.
Progressive loss of previously present language abilities.
The presence of multiple cysts in both kidneys.
Abnormally decreased levels of serine in cerebrospinal fluid.
A reduction in the amplitude of sensory nerve action potential. This feature is measured by nerve conduction studies.
Abnormal closure or blockage of the vas deferens.
Seizures characterized by olfactory phenomena as its first clinical manifestation.

An abnormal degree of flatness of the Ala of nose, which can be defined as a reduced nasal elevation index (lateral depth of the nose from the tip of the nose to the insertion of the nasal ala in the cheek x 100 divided by the side-to-side breadth of the nasal alae).
An abnormally decreased concentration of leukotriene C4 in the blood circulation.

A type of anomalous trichromacy associated with defective long-wavelength-sensitive (L) cones, causing the sensitivity spectrum to be shifted toward medium wavelengths. This leads to difficulties especially in distinguishing red and green.
Abnormally increased levels of alanine in cerebrospinal fluid.
Abnormality of the oral mucosa.
Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements of equal velocity.
Hard, pebble-like deposits that form within the gallbladder.
A focal seizure with automatism in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.
Excess facial hair.
Testicular inflammation.

A midline anterior-posterior cleft of the epiglottis that involves at least two-thirds of the epiglottic leaf. It is a useful feature for clinical diagnosis because it appears to be very rare in syndromes other than Pallister-Hall-Syndrome and is also rare as an isolated malformation.
Encephalomalacia is the softening or loss of brain tissue after cerebral infarction, cerebral ischemia, infection, craniocerebral trauma, or other injury.
Auras with affective, mnemonic or composite perceptual phenomena including illusory or composite hallucinatory events.
A condition associated with a limitation of the horizontal ocular movement with retraction of the globe and narrowing of the palpebral fissure on adduction
Any anomaly of the structure of the uterus
A reduction in the ability of the kidneys to remove uric acid from the serum.
Absence of thumb nail.
Radiolucent focal defect of a rib shaft.

A condition which is considered to be due to the subsequent atrophy and disappearance in fetal life of an initially normal testis. In the presence of spermatic cord structures is evidence of the presence of the testis in early intrauterine life. When associated with a blind-ending spermatic cord, this entity is named as his absence of a testis in an otherwise normal 46XY male is usually unilateral and is assumed to be a consequence of intrauterine or perinatal torsion or infarction.
The narrowing or partial blockage of a portion of the duodenum.
A decreased amount of tryptophan in the blood.
Anterior tongue-like protrusions of the vertebral bodies.

A separation of the layers within the wall of the ascending aorta. Tears in the intimal layer result in the propagation of dissection (proximally or distally) secondary to blood entering the intima-media space.
Decreased strength of the superior rectus muscle.
Increased size of the semicircular canal.
The presence of inflammatory changes in the gallbladder.

The presence of one or more dendritic corneal epithelial ulcers characterized by a treelike branching linear pattern with feathery edges and terminal bulbs. Herpetiform corneal ulcers can be identified by fluorescein staining.
Congenital anomaly characterized by closure or failure to develop an opening in the urethra.
Hyperplasia of lining epithelia of the septal and large bile ducts manifesting as micropapillary projections or as a stratification of the epithelium with or without dilatation of the duct lumen.
A partial dislocation of the intervertebral joint between the second and third cervical vertebrae.
Blindness with onset at birth.
Abnormally increased levels of glutamine in cerebrospinal fluid.
A nodular pattern on pulmonary high-resolution computed tomography that has an apparently random pattern.
Increased top to bottom height of vertebral bodies.
Recurrent attacks of severe anxiety, whose occurence is not restricted to any particular situation or set of circumstances and is therefore unpredictable.
Increased prominence of the xiphoid process of the sternum.
Choroidal neovascularization (CNV) is the creation of new blood vessels in the choroid layer of the eye.
A structural abnormality of the sperm tail.
Partial displacement of the lens in the inferior direction.
A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the scalp.
Any abnormality of the alveolar ridges (on the upper or lower jaws). The alveolar ridges contain the sockets (alveoli) of the teeth.
The deposition of calcium phosphate microliths within the seminiferous tubules.
An abnormality of the renal tubules.
A decreased concentration of methionine in the blood.
Any abnormality in the serum transferrin saturation, which is calculated by dividing the serum iron level by total iron-binding capacity.
Osteosclerosis affecting one or more bones of the hand.
Decreased width of the nasal ridge.

A failure to achieve the ability to walk at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children learn to walk in a series of stages, and learn to walk short distances independently between 12 and 15 months.
A type of focal bilateral motor seizure during which awareness is fully retained throughout.
An abnormal bulge or lump in a testis. A testicular mass has a long differential diagnosis including testicular torsion, epididymitis, acute orchitis, strangulated hernia and testicular cancer.

The presence of a cleft in the oral cavity, the two main types of which are cleft lip and cleft palate. In cleft lip, there is the congenital failure of the maxillary and median nasal processes to fuse, forming a groove or fissure in the lip. In cleft palate, there is a congenital failure of the palate to fuse properly, forming a grooved depression or fissure in the roof of the mouth. Clefts of the lip and palate can occur individually or together. It is preferable to code each defect separately.
Congenital underdevelopment of the iris.
Underdevelopment of the brainstem.
Abnormally decreased levels of arginine in cerebrospinal fluid.
The presence of a fistula of the vagina.
Excessive action of the medial rectus muscle caused by increased innervation typically as a consequence of palsy or limitation to the ipsilateral antagonist or contralateral synergist.
An abnormally increased calcium concentration in the blood.
Underdevelopment of the urinary bladder.
A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a diffuse hypointensity affecting the entire brainstem.
Atrophy of the cortex of the kidney.

A type of retinal detachment associated with a retinal tear, that is, with a break in the retina that allows fluid to pass from the vitreous space into the subretinal space between the sensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.
Absence of the semicircular canal.
Deterioration or loss of the tissues of the saccule of the vestibule.

An intermittent atrioventricular block with failure of some atrial impulses to conduct to the ventricles, i.e., some but not all atrial impulses are conducted through the atrioventricular node and trigger ventricular contraction.
Any ventricular septal defect (VSD) that does not restrict flow across it sufficiently to generate a pressure gradient between the two sides of the VSD.
Enlarged, bulging blood vessels in and around the anus often associated with rectal bleeding, itching, and pain.
Small, underdeveloped vertebral bodies.
Two penile structures, separated from the tip to the base of the shaft.
Obstruction of the flow of urine through the urethra.
Increased amount of autofluorescence in the macula as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.
A diminution of the peripheral visual field whereby at least 50 degrees of central field are preserved in all meridians.

An elevation in the ratio of the diameter of the cup of the optic disc to the total diameter of the disc. The optic disc has an orange-pink rim with a pale centre (the cup) that does not contain neuroretinal tissue. An increase in this ratio therefore may indicate a decrease in the quantity of healthy neuroretinal cells.
U wave inversion that is induced by exercise stress testing.
The presence of xanthine-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.
Increased susceptibility to Haemophilus influenzae infections as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection by Haemophilus influenzae.
A cleft of the xiphoid process of the sternum.

Osteoporosis is a systemic skeletal disease characterized by low bone density and microarchitectural deterioration of bone tissue with a consequent increase in bone fragility. According to the WHO criteria, osteoporosis is defined as a BMD that lies 2.5 standard deviations or more below the average value for young healthy adults (a T-score below -2.5 SD).
A form of hydrocephalus in which there is no visible obstruction to the flow of the cerebrospinal fluid between the ventricles and subarachnoid space.
A splitting of the nasal tip. Visually assessable vertical indentation, cleft, or depression of the nasal tip.
A form of sensorineural hearing impairment with onset after the acquisition of speech.
A focal motor seizure with paresis / paralysis characterized by impaired awareness at some point during the seizure.
Reduced transparency of the central portion of the corneal stroma.
An epidermoid cyst in the armpit.

Blockage at the level of the bladder and the ureter caused by stenosis of the ureteral valves or failure of a narrow juxtavesical ureteral segment to dilate due to segmented fibrosis or localized absence of muscle.
Areflexia that is limited to one side of the body.
A severe delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.
The length of the incisura from the upper to lower border is less than that observed in the average population.
An abnormality of XY sexual development characterized by the absence of both testes at birth.

Absence of the normal opening of a coronary ostium. There are normally two coronary ostia, which are site of origin of the main left or right main coronary artery and are located in the ascending aorta just above the aortic valve.
A structural abnormality of the sperm mid-piece.
Decreased strength (ability to move) of the lateral rectus muscle.

Presence of interstitial mononuclear leukocytes, i.e., white blood ceclls with a single round nucleus, including lymphocytes and monocytes but not including granulocytes (which have multilobed nuclei).
Abnormally increased levels of glutamic acid in cerebrospinal fluid.
Abnormally decreased levels of glutamine in cerebrospinal fluid.
A rudimentary tag of ear tissue often containing a core of cartilage and located just in back of the auricle (outer part of the ear).
Visually assessable vertical indentation, cleft, or depression of the nasal bridge, ridge and tip.
A partial reduction in level of the complement component Factor H in circulation.
Lack of convexity or prominence of the contour of the ridge between the bottom of the incisura and the confluence of the ascending helix and crus helix.
Decreased amount of autofluorescence in the macula as ascertained by fundus autofluorescence imaging.

A large reduction in the fraction of blood pumped from the left ventricle with each cardiac cycle. The normal range in adults is at over 50 percent, and a severe reduction is defined as less than 30 percent.

Anomalous coronary origin whereby the left anterior descending (LAD) and the left circumflex artery (LCX) arise separately. Normally, these arteries arise from a common stem, the left main coronary artery (LMCA).
Increased width of the ischium, which forms the lower and back part of the hip bone.

Hemosiderin-laden macrophages (HLM) in bronchoalveolar lavage (BAL) fluid were originally known as adiagnostic biomarker of alveolar hemorrhage, but have also been observed in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF) with histopathological pattern of usual interstitial pneumonia (UIP).
A form of nephrotic syndrome that does not respond to treatment with steroid medication.
Abnormal persistent patency of the ductus arteriosus in postnatal life when birth was at 37 completed weeks of gestation or greater.
Excessive wrinkling of the skin of the face.
The presence of a vaginal septum, thereby creating a vaginal duplication. The septum is longitudinal in the majority of cases.
A reduced concentration of zinc in the blood.
Astigmatism in which the refractive power of the vertical meridian is the greatest.
An abnormal increase in the concentration of monosialylated core 1 O-glycans on glycoproteins.
Dryness of the mouth due to salivary gland dysfunction.
Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen.
A progressive form of decreased height of the intervertebral disk.
An increased concentration of isoleucine in the blood.
Lens of the eye is smaller than normal and spherically shaped.
Absence or underdevelopment of the nasal septum.
Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements, in which the movement in one direction is faster than in the other.
A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration in the distal portions of the limbs.
Underdevelopment of the olfactory bulb.
Abnormal depth of the S wave in lead V5 of the electrocardiogram.
A seizure characterized by sensory phenomena including tingling, numbness, electric-shock like sensation, pain, sense of movement, or desire to move as its first clinical manifestation.
Any structural abnormality of the cerebellum.

Patchy (irregular) changes in bone mineral density with patches of bone showing an increased density side to side with patches that are affected by reduction of mineral density. This is sometimes referred to as a moth-eaten appearance on x-rays.
An decreased concentration of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
Dilation and elongation of the penile urethra associated with absence or hypoplasia of the corpora spongiosa and cavernosa.
An avascular or abnormally vascularized retina that occurs in premature infants and can lead to blindness.
Abnormally increased levels of serine in cerebrospinal fluid.
An elevated concentration of glycine in the blood.
An abnormally increased sodium concentration in the blood.
Underdevelopment of the semicircular canal.
Diffuse slowing of cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
A congenital absence or considerable underdevelopment of the trachea such that communication between the larynx proximally and the alveoli of the lungs distally is lacking.
Any abnormality of the teeth.
Lack of skin pigmentation (coloring) of the abdomen.

Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at one or more long bones in the foot, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.

An abnormality of corticomedullary differentiation (CMD) on diagnostic imaging such as magnetic resonance imaging, computer tomography, or sonography. CMD is a difference in the visualization of cortex and medulla.
An abnormal curvature of the spine in both a coronal (lateral) and sagittal (back-to-front) plane.
A type of gait ataxia displaying progression of clinical severity.
A primitive neuroectodermal neoplasm that occurs in the central nervous system.
Marked widening of the trachea and major bronchi that may be predispose to chronic respiratory tract infection.
A conduction block of the left branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a generalized disturbance of QRS morphology on EKG.
An anomaly of the small joints located between and behind adjacent vertebrae.
An ocular movement abnormality characterised by simultaneous weakness of the inferior rectus muscle and superior oblique muscle of the same eye.
Over curvature of the thoracic region, leading to a round back or if sever to a hump.

A type of retinal detachment arising due to a combination of contracting retinal membranes, abnormal vitreoretinal adhesions, and vitreous changes. It is usually seen in the context of diseases that induce a fibrovascular response, e.g. diabetes.
The presence of more than two testes.

A skin condition characterized by excessive development of keratin in hair follicles, resulting in rough, cone-shaped, elevated papules resulting from closure of hair follicles with a white plug of sebum.
A decreased amount of alanine in the blood.
Inflammation of the ileum.

An epithelial lined cyst filled with gelatinous material. The gelatinous material commonly contains mucin, old blood, cholesterol, and ions. Most colloid cysts identified are currently asymptomatic and identified incidentally on imaging. When a colloid cyst does cause issues, it most commonly causes obstructive hydrocephalus.
Multiple pigmented macules located on the skin of the penis.
A congenital defect with failure to open of the mitral valve orifice.
Reduced count of spermatozoa in the semen, defined as a sperm count below 20 million per milliliter semen.
Accumulation of blood in the vagina usually due to vaginal obstruction.

Anomalous mitral valve arcade is diagnosed based on the following features (1) An adequately sized mitral valve orifice; (2) short, thick, and poorly differentiated chordae with direct union of the papillary muscles to the anterior leaflet; (3) narrow or nearly nonexistent spaces between the abnormal chordae; and (4) greater differentiation of the chordae attached to the posterior papillary muscle.
The presence of a row of multiple rounded expansions (beadlike prominences) at the junction of a rib and its cartilage.
A decreased amount of glutamate in the blood.
Well-demarcated area(s) of partial or complete depigmentation in the fundus, reflecting atrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium with associated retinal photoreceptor loss.
Atrophy of the cervical segment of the spinal cord.
Fasciculations affecting the tongue muscle and the musculature of the chin.
Underdeveloped scapula.

Increased frequency of theta wave activity in the electroencephalogram. Theta waves have a frequency of 3.5-7.5 Hertz, and are present in very small amounts in healthy waking adult EEGs. Theta activity is normal in small very amounts in the healthy waking adult EEG in a symmetrical distribution.
An abnormality of the pons.
A focal motor seizure with version characterized by impaired awareness at some point during the seizure.
The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in one or more epiphyses.
Having only one testis in the scrotum.
When viewed in lateral radiographs, vertebral bodies have a roughly rectangular configuration. This term applies if the vertebral body appears rounded or oval.

Osteopenia is a term to define bone density that is not normal but also not as low as osteoporosis. By definition from the World Health Organization osteopenia is defined by bone densitometry as a T score -1 to -2.5.
A focal motor seizure with negative myoclonus characterized by impairement of awareness at some point during the seizure.
A cone-shaped deformity of the cornea characterized by the presence of corneal distortion secondary to thinning of the apex.
A medium reduction in the fraction of blood pumped from the left ventricle with each cardiac cycle.
Left ventricular noncompaction (LVNC) is defined by 3 markers: prominent left ventricular (LV) trabeculae, deep intertrabecular recesses, and the thin compacted layer.
A form of hydrocephalus in which the flow of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) within the cerebral ventricular system or in the outlets of the CSF to the arachnoid space is obstructed.
A fixed form of obstruction to blood flow across the left-ventricular outflow tract related to stenosis (narrowing) below the level of the aortic valve.
Decreased length of O-fucosylated glycans present on properdin.
Reduced addition of mannose to N-linked glycans.

Subcortical heterotopia consisting of a bilateral and symmetric single continuous, undulating ribbon-like layer of gray matter located in the frontal, parietal and occipital lobes. It has no visible connection to the overlying cortex.
Any increased amount from normal of valine in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Presence of biliary veins that serve as a collateral channel to the systemic circulation

A type of anomalous trichromacy associated with abnormal M photopigment, such that the absorption spectrum is shifted toward L wavelengths. Affected individuals have difficulties distinguishing between red and green.
Inflammation of interstitial tissues of the kidney consisting of foamy macrophages admixed with plasma cells, lymphocytes and neutrophils and occasional giant cells.
Dilation and elongation of the duodenum with hypertrophy of all layers of the duodenum.
The presence of a partially duplicated kidney.
A form of hyperkeratosis characterized by thickening of the cornified layer without retained nuclei.
Accumulation of lipids in alveolar macrophages with droplet-shaped fat inclusions.
A form of nephrotic syndrome that does not respond to any immunosuppresive treatment.
Abnormal persistent patency of the ductus arteriosus when birth was at less than 37 weeks completed gestation.
Abnormally elevated blood carbon dioxide (CO2) level in the cord blood.
A partial or complete positional exchange between the penis and the scrotum, with positioning of the scrotum superior to the penis.

An elevation in the total-iron binding capacity, which measures how much serum iron is bound if an excess of radioactive iron is added. A high TIBC corresponds to a high transferrin concentration. The latent (or free) iron binding capacity is the difference between the TIBC and the measured serum iron, corresponding to the transferrin not bound to iron, i.e., free iron binding capacity.

A duplication of the collecting system of the kidney, defined as a kidney with two (instead of, normally, one) pyelocaliceal systems. The pyelocaliceal system is comprised of the renal pelvis and calices. The duplicated renal collecting system can be associated with a single ureter or with double ureters. In the latter case, the two ureters empty separately into the bladder or fuse to form a single ureteral orifice.
A type of ichthyosiform erythroderma with postnatal onset.
An abnormal dilatation of the fourth cerebral ventricle.

Trophic changes is a term used to describe abnormalities in the area of pain that include primarily wasting away of the skin, tissues, or muscle, thinning of the bones, and changes in how the hair or nails grow, including thickening or thinning of hair or brittle nails.
Lack of ossification of the sacrum.
A tricuspid valve that has failed to open.
Focal non-convulsive status epilepticus without coma is a type of status epilepticus without prominent motor signs, which is electrographically focal. It is a prolonged focal non-motor seizure.
Delay of conduction through the atrioventricular node, which is manifested as prolongation of the PR interval in the electrocardiogram (EKG). All atrial impulses reach the ventricles.
An anomaly of the outer labia.
Reduced echogenicity of liver tissue on sonography, manifested as an increased amount of black on the screen of the sonography device.
A reduction in the speed at which electrical signals propagate along the axon of a neuron.
A type of incomitant strabismus in which both elevator muscles (i.e., the inferior oblique and superior rectus muscles) of the same eye are weak leading to restricted elevation and hypotropia.
Lack of a palpable nasal cartilage.

A focal collection of 20 or more red blood cells within the interstitium, that is irregular in shape (i.e., collections do not conform to the shape of tubules or capillary networks), without surrounding endothelium or tubular epithelium, and is in an area of intact core.
A type of age-related cataract consisting of granular opacities occurring mainly in the central posterior cortex just under the posterior capsule.
A two-sided form of atrophy of the kidney.
A partial or complete breakage of the ilium.

Absence of the inner dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, which normally are situated within the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.
Apparent optic disc swelling in the absence of increased intracranial pressure.
An increased concentration of lysine in the blood.
The circumflex coronary artery originates from the right aortic sinus of Valsalva.
Absence of the vestibular nerve
A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary undressing at onset.
Significant luminal narrowing of a long segment of or the entire ascending aorta.
Generalised myoclonic-tonic-clonic seizure provoked by flashing or flickering light.
A lump detected in the prostate. In this context, mass is a general term for a lump or growth that may be caused by the abnormal growth of cells, a cyst, hormonal changes, or an immune reaction.

Thinned, erythematous, depressed bands of atrophic skin. Initially, striae appear as flattened and thinned, pinkish linear regions of the skin. Striae tend to enlarge in length and become reddish or purplish. Later, striae tend to appear as white, depressed bands that are parallel to the lines of skin tension. Striae distensae occur most often in areas that have been subject to distension such as the lower back, buttocks, thighs, breast, abdomen, and shoulders.

Vitreomacular traction is characterized by anomalous posterior vitreous detachment accompanied by anatomic distortion of the fovea, which may include pseudocysts, macular schisis, cystoid macular edema, and subretinal fluid. Vitreomacular traction can be subclassified by the diameter of vitreous attachment to the macular surface as measured by OCT, with attachment of 1500 micrometers or less defined as focal and attachment of more than 1500 micrometers as broad.
Any abnormality of the mouth floor.
Decreased strength of the inferior rectus muscle.
A focal cognitive seizure characterized by dyslexia / alexia as the initial semiological manifestation.
Increased amplitude (0.1 mV or more) and/or duration (40 ms or more) of the S wave as measured in lead I of the electrocardiogram.
A type of transposition of the great arteries (TGA) in which aorta is in front of and primarily to the left of the pulmonary artery.
An abnormal increase in the amount of intracellular lipid droplets in hepatocytes.
Developmental hypoplasia of the cochlea.
A decreased amount of proline in the blood.
Abnormal transferrin isoform profile consistent with a type II congenital disorder of glycosylation.
Wasting (atrophy) of the testicle (the male gonad) manifested by a decrease in size and potentially by a loss of fertility.
A reduced level of the complement component C6 in the blood circulation.

Interrupted inferior vena cava with azygous continuation is the result of connection failure between the right subcardinal vein and the right vitelline vein. Consequently, venous blood from the caudal part of the body reaches the heart via the azygous vein and superior vena cava.
Astigmatism with more plus power on the horizontal meridian.
Any decreased amount from normal of valine in the cerebrospinal fluid.

This corneal dystrophy affects the posterior limiting membrane of the cornea and is characterized by polymorphous plaques of calcium deposits in the deep stromal layers of the cornea, and occasionally by vesicular lesions of the endothelium and edema of the deep corneal stroma.
A form of astigmatism in which one meridian is hyperopic while the one at a right angle to it has no refractive error.
Congenital absence of the optic nerve.
Ribs with a reduced diameter.
An abnormal increase in the concentration of sialylated N-glycans on glycoproteins.
A type of focal-onset epileptic spasm in which awareness is preserved throughout the seizure.
A fluid filled sac located in the Fallopian tube.
A broad chest.
Any structural anomaly of the leaflets (also known as cusps) of the mitral valve.
Increased echogenicity of liver tissue on sonography, manifested as an increased amount of white on the screen of the sonography device.

A longer than normal interval (corrected for heart rate) between the Q and T waves in the heart's cycle. Prolonged QTc can cause premature action potentials during late phase depolarizations thereby leading to ventricular arrhythmias and ventricular fibrillations.
A type of incomitant strabismus in which the angle of deviation varies as the patient's gaze shifts upwards and/or downwards.
Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

A conduction block of the right branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a prolongation of the QRS complex (greater than 0.12 s) with delayed activation of the right ventricle and terminal delay on the EKG.
Presence of a single diverticulum (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urinary bladder.
A decreased amount of threonine in the blood.
Patchy (irregular) reduction in bone density. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at one or more long bones in the hand, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.
Bleeding into the biliary tree.
A thinning out of elastic fibers of the media of the aorta that creates widening of intralamellar spaces, as identified on a stain for elastic fibers.
An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation (reduced or absent) of the iris and retina.
A focal tonic seizure in which awareness is partially or fully impaired at some point during the seizure.

The ilia is round and hypoplastic with a very flat acetabular roof and a very unusual medial projection of bone that is said to resemble the head of a snail. Figure 4 of PMID:3799723 illustrates this feature.
A partial or complete breakage of the thoracic vertebra.

A congenital, hairless plaque consisting of overgrown epidermis, sebaceous glands, hair follicles, apocrine glands and connective tissue. They are a variant of epidermal naevi. Sebaceous naevi most often appear on the scalp, but they may also arise on the face, neck or forehead. At birth, a sevaceous nevus typically appears as a solitary, smooth, yellow-orange hairless patch. Sebaceous naevi become more pronounced around adolescence, often appearing bumpy, warty or scaly.
Degeneration of the olivary bodies, prominent oval structures in the medulla oblongata.
Increased susceptibility to Klebsiella infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Klebsiella infection.
Lack of prominence of the nose resulting from a posteriorly-placed nasal ridge.
Autonomic status epilepticus is a type of non-convulsive status epilepticus without coma with prominent autonomic features regardless of whether it is electrographically generalized or focal.
The presence of an aortic valve with one instead of the normal three cusps (flaps).
Lack of formation (congenital absence) of the olfactory bulb.
A decreased amount of isoleucine in the blood.
A congenital cataract in which opacity is limited to layers of the lens external to the nucleus (i.e., the perinuclear region), i.e., between the nuclear and cortical layers of the lens.
A macular hole is a small break in the macula, located in the center of the retina.
A structural abnormality of the sperm neck.

An inherited retinal disease subtype in which the rod photoreceptors appear to be more severely affected than the cone photoreceptors. Typical presentation is with nyctalopia (due to rod dysfunction) followed by loss of mid-peripheral field of vision, which gradually extends and leaves many patients with a small central island of vision due to the preservation of macular cones.
Alternating and recurrent weakness of the external ocular muscles.
A reduced level of the complement component C4a in circulation.
Increased susceptibility to Serratia marcescens infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Serratia marcescens infection.
A seizure characterized by sensations of feeling hot or cold as its first clinical manifestation.
A progressive form of scoliosis with congenital onset.
A type of focal autonomic seizure characterised by penile erection as the intial semiological feature.

Incoordination of movement caused by a deficit in the sensory nervous system. Sensory ataxia can be distinguished from cerebellar ataxia by asking the patient to close his or her eyes. Persons with cerebellar ataxia show only a minimal worsening of symptoms, whereas persons with sensory ataxia show a marked worsening of symptoms.
A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by involuntary sexual behavior at onset.
A focal motor seizure with negative myoclonus characterized by retained awareness throughout the seizure.
Any anomaly of ovarian function.
Loss of peripheral vision with retention of central vision, resulting in a constricted circular tunnel-like field of vision.
Solid nodular heterotopia situated in the region of the peritrigonal optic pathway posterior to the deep gray nuclei.
Diffuse enlargement of the entire cerebral hemispheres leading to macrocephaly (with or without overlying cortical dysplasia).
A primitive neuroectodermal neoplasm that occurs extracranially in soft tissue and bone.

A swelling formed at the base of umbilicus associated with a patent urachus which results from an allantoic remnant. The urachus is a fibrous remnant of the allantois which communicates from the apex of the urinary bladder to the umbilicus. Failed obliteration of the urachus can lead to various abnormalities: urachal cyst, urachal diverticulum, sinus or patent urachus - the most common type. Allantoic cysts in infants with patent urachus can be formed due to the drainage of urine into the umbilical cord, or in uncommon situations, after leakage of hypo-osmotic urine into the Wharton's jelly.
Lack of development of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.
Bulbous appearance of the anterior vertebral bodies, such that the vertebral bodies have the greatest vertical height anteriorly as well as bulbous anterior superior-inferior contours.
Abnormal ossification (bone tissue formation) affecting the pubic bone, also known as the pubis.
Developmental defect resulting in congenital absence of the middle portion of the clavicle.
A decreased amount of hydroxyproline in the blood.
Absence or underdevelopment of the gallbladder.

A diffusion abnormality observed in diffusion-weighted magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brain. Molecular diffusion refers to the notion that any type of molecule in a fluid (eg, water) is randomly displaced as the molecule is agitated by thermal energy. Restricted diffusion of water appears bright on diffusion-weighted images.
A limitation of the ability to direct one's gaze above the horizontal meridian.
An increased CPK level between 4X and 50X above the upper normal level.
Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with an symmetrical and concentric pattern of hypertrophy.
A type of focal clonic seizure during which awareness is fully retained throughout.
An increase in bone density within the clavicle.
The presence of a diverticulum (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urethra.
A reduced level of the complement component C8 in circulation.
An abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the thoracic aorta.
Deposits accumulating between the retinal pigment epithelium and Bruch's membrane and that are distributed in multiple foci.

Ultra-low vision but with retained ability to perceive the difference between light and dark. Also when light is projected in each of the four quadrants of the visual field, the individual is able to correctly identify the origin of the light stimulus.
A conical projection of the posterior surface of the lens, occurring as a developmental anomaly.
Reduced concentration of serine in the blood.

An acute condition characterized by sudden visual loss (usually discovered in the morning), optic disc edema at onset, optic disc-related visual field defects. Nonarteritic anterior ischemic optic neuropathy can be associated with flame hemorrhages on the swollen disc or nearby neuroretinal layer, and sometimes with nearby cotton-wool exudates.

A failure to achieve the ability to stand up at an appropriate developmental stage. Most children begin to walk alone at 11 to 15 months of age. On average, children can stand while holding on at the age of 9 to 10 months, can pull up to stand and walk with one hand being held at 12 months, and can stand alone and walk well at 18 months.
A small reduction in the fraction of blood pumped from the left ventricle with each cardiac cycle. The normal range in adults is at least 50 percent, and a mild reduction is defined as 40-49 percent.
A form of strabismus with one or both eyes turned inward ('crossed') to a relatively severe degree, usually defined as 10 diopters or more.
A reduced level of the complement component C5 in the blood circulation.
An eyelid myoclonia seizure is a type of generalized myoclonic seizure which may or may not be associated with loss of awareness.
A smooth, extratesticular, spherical cyst in the head of the epididymis.

A type of focal motor status epilepticus characterized by continuous neck or body rotation and conjugate gaze deviation in a direction contralateral to the responsible epileptic focus. This includes some forms of tonic status epilepticus.
Increased protrusion of the antihelical ridge, proximal to its bifurcation, relative to the prominence of the helix.
Punched out lesions in the pigmented layer of the retina.
Any structural anomaly of the chordae tendinae of the tricuspid valve. The chordae tendineae connect the papillary muscles to the tricuspid valve.
Congenital occlusion of the vagina or adhesion of the walls of the vagina causing occlusion.

A type of focal automatism seizure characterized by coordinated bilateral or unilateral movements of the feet or legs at onset. The movement is more reminiscent of normal movements in amplitude, and is less frenetic or rapid in comparison to the movements seen in focal hyperkinetic seizures involving the legs.
A form of sensorineural hearing impairment with infantile onset.
Any abnormality of the tongue.
A small break in the retina.
A cavity within the cerebral hemisphere, filled with cerebrospinal fluid, that communicates directly with the ventricular system.

Left ventricular non-compaction (LVNC) is characterized by prominent left ventricular trabeculae and deep inter-trabecular recesses. The myocardial wall is often thickened with a thin, compacted epicardial layer and a thickened endocardial layer. In some patients, LVNC is associated with left ventricular dilatation and systolic dysfunction, which can be transient in neonates.
An increase in the amount of very-low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
Accumulation of globotriaosylceramide (GL-3) in kidney tissues, which can be quantified as the number of globotriaosylceramide (GL-3) inclusions/kidney interstitial capillary (KIC).

Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at one or more long bones in the fibula, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.
A reduced level of the complement component C9 in circulation.
Weakness or partial paralysis in the lower limbs.
Non-continuity of the arch of aorta with an atretic point or absent segment.
If positive, the ferric chloride test indicates an increased concentration of phenols in the urine or blood.

Focal emotional seizure with crying (dacrystic) is characterized by the presence of stereotyped crying, this may be accompanied by lacrimation, sad facial expression and sobbing. The subjective emotion of sadness may or may not be present.
Wide, concave rib end.
Abnormal conduction in all three divisions of the intraventricular conducting tissue.
A reduction in the amount of very-low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
The left common carotid artery normally originates from the aortic arch. This term refers to an origin of this artery from the brachiocephalic artery.
Decreased concentration of lactate in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Abnormally increased width of the pubic symphysis is the midline cartilaginous joint uniting the superior rami of the left and right pubic bones.
A seizure characterized by symptoms of dizziness, spinning, vertigo or sense of rotation as its first clinical manifestation.
Presence of struvite (magnesium ammonium phosphate) containing calculi (kidney stones).
An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement affecting the lip.
Origin of the right coronary artery (RCA) from the left sinus of Valsalva or of the left main (LM) or left anterior descending (LAD) coronary artery from the right sinus of Valsalva.
An abnormally increased thickness of a leaflet of the aortic valve.
A focal behavior arrest seizure characterised by impaired awareness at some point during the seizure.
A decrease in the volume (size) of the amygdyla.
The presence of an extracardiac channel that connects the ascending aorta above the sinotubular junction to the cavity of the right ventricle.

Apical hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (AHCM) is diastolic dysfunction due to abnormal stiffness of the left ventricle during diastole, with resultant impaired ventricular filling. In AHCM thickened apical segments produce a crowded, spade-shaped, small apical cavity.
Loose and sagging skin often associated with loss of skin elasticity.
Sharply demarcated, congenital hyperpigmentation of the retinal pigment epithelium.
Any abnormality of the vertebral end plates, which are the top and bottom portions of the vertebral bodies that interface with the vertebral discs.
